{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500025"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:07:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:07:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1600"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1600"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.15,0.34,0.03,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77073"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1600"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62579"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"728"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3800"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46474"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77073"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner for annual check-up. She is in good health but described a cough that has been bothering her most of winter. It began about one month ago, comes, and goes and is non-productive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer other medical conditions include gastro-oesophageal reflux disease for which she takes 20mg/d pantoprazole. She smoked 15 cigarettes per day since her early 20s and quit five years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her chest sounds clear and heart sounds are dual with no murmurs. She has no peripheral oedema, and her vital signs are within normal range. Her abdomen is soft, non-tender and not distended. Bowel sounds are heard.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe GP orders a chest X-ray (Image):\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dextrocardia","Paraoesophageal hernia","Eventration of the diaphragm","Perforated viscus","Emphysematous bulla"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chest x-ray demonstrates a thin rim of diaphragm that is raised above the air-filled stomach on the left-hand side, which is quite distended with gas making the eventration more obvious. The most likely cause of this is \u003Cstrong\u003Eeventration of the diaphragm\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition refers to the abnormal contour of the diaphragmatic dome. Congenitally this can present as respiratory distress in the newborn period, whilst in adults it is often asymptomatic, as in this case. Acquired causes include trauma/surgery causing phrenic nerve paralysis. Her cough is unlikely to be related to this diaphragmatic abnormality but could be early signs of emphysema or lung damage from her significant smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe heart has been pushed over to the right due to the eventration of the diaphragm, giving the appearance of dextrocardia, but it is not true \u003Cstrong\u003Edextrocardia.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforated viscus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause free air under the diaphragm also called a pneumoperitoneum. This looks similar to this x-ray, but the gas under the diaphragm in this film is contained within the stomach wall and is not free air. Additionally, she would be likely to have symptoms if she had a perforated viscus such as abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA bulla is an air filled bubble \u0026gt;1cm within the lung. The bubble of air seen in this image is seen within the stomach, not the lungs. Therefore this does not represent \u003Cstrong\u003Eemphysematous bulla.\u003C/strong\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eparaoesophageal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E also called a hiatus hernia could be causing symptoms of reflux, which she has a history of but the image is not consistent with this.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Eventration of the diaphragm refers to abnormal contour of the diaphragmatic dome.","Eventration of the diaphragm can be congenital or acquired, often asymptomatic in adults."],"references":["Vadera S, Radswiki et al, 2021. Diaphragmatic eventration. Radiopaedia. Access at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/diaphragmatic-eventration.","Dikme O. Perforated Viscus. International Emergency Medicine Education Project. Access at: https://iem-student.org/perforated-viscus/.","Tiryaki T, Livanelio\u011flu Z, Atayurt H. Eventration of the diaphragm. Asian J Surg. 2006 Jan;29(1):8-10. doi: 10.1016/S1015-9584(09)60285-2. PMID: 16428090.","Agarwal AK, Lone NA. Diaphragm Eventration. 2024 Aug 11. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809332."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62579"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1600"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18386"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18386"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/62e588a7-0b8e-4911-b459-2730cf1d6cb5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/62e588a7-0b8e-4911-b459-2730cf1d6cb5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":484,"height":44